Therefore, the peak wavelength is 48 Angstroms. **Final Answer** The peak wavelength is \boxed{48} Angstroms. </think> To find the peak wavelength of the emitted radiation from the star, we use Wien's displacement law, which states that the wavelength of maximum emission \(\lambda_{\text{max}}\) is given by: \[ \lambda_{\text{max}} = \frac{b}{T} \] where \(b\) is Wien's displacement constant (\(2.898 \times 10^{-3} \, \text{m} \cdot \text{K}\)) and \(T\) is the temperature of the star. Given the temperature \(T = 6 \times 10^{5} \, \text{K}\), we compute: \[ \lambda_{\text{max}} = \frac{2.898 \times 10^{-3} \, \text{m} \cdot \text{K}}{6 \times 10^{5} \, \text{K}} = \frac{2.898 \times 10^{-3}}{6 \times 10^{5}} \, \text{m} \] Converting meters to Angstroms (1 m = \(10^{10}\) Angstroms): \[ \lambda_{\text{max}} = \left( \frac{2.898 \times 10^{-3}}{6 \times 10^{5}} \right) \times 10^{10} \, \text{Angstroms} = \frac{2.898 \times 10^{2}}{6} \, \text{Angstroms} = 48.3 \, \text{Angstroms} \] Rounding to the nearest whole number, the peak wavelength is: \[ \boxed{48} \, \text{Angstroms} \]
